## 5. Spatial Relationship Descriptions

### 5.1 Building Mass → surrounds → Courtyard

The main building mass wraps around a central courtyard. This creates an inward-facing communal space protected from the surrounding city.

### 5.2 Courtyard → organizes → Residential Units

The courtyard acts as the spatial center of the project. Residential units are arranged around it, giving many units a visual or spatial relationship with the shared garden.

### 5.3 Sloped Roof → opens → Courtyard to Sky

The sloped roof form lowers one side of the mass and opens the courtyard toward the sky. This improves light access and reduces the sense of enclosure.

### 5.4 High-Rise Corner → concentrates → Residential Density

The building rises at one corner to provide high-rise density while allowing other parts of the building to remain lower and more open.

### 5.5 Perimeter Block → defines → Urban Edge

The building completes an urban block edge while also transforming the block into a three-dimensional residential form.

### 5.6 Amenity Spaces → activate → Courtyard

Shared amenities such as the swimming pool, basketball court, fitness studio, community room, and game room are located around the courtyard. These programs activate the internal open space.

### 5.7 Residential Corridor → connects → Apartment Modules

Corridors connect repeated apartment units along the perimeter of the courtyard and the exterior facade.

### 5.8 Massing Diagram → transforms → Block Typology

The massing diagram shows a transformation from a simple block to a courtyard block and then to a sloped courtscraper. This demonstrates a typological shift from flat block to hybrid tower.

### 5.9 Courtyard → mediates → City and Domestic Life

The courtyard provides a shared landscape that mediates between private housing units and the dense city surrounding the site.

### 5.10 Sloped Massing → balances → Views and Density

The sloped massing allows the building to maintain high density while improving daylight, views, and courtyard openness.

